          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              While technically correct, the Ars article omits an extremely important point from the NYT source:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> It is queried for phone numbers of interest mainly using what are called “administrative subpoenas,” those issued not by a grand jury or a judge but by a federal agency, in this case the D.E.A. </div><br /><br />That's right, this data is received by the DEA with absolutely no court oversight.<br /><br />There is an aspect of this that is important and reasonable. In my opinion, the three problems are:<br />1) No court oversight.<br />2) 26 years is too much data to retain. Far, far beyond what is appropriate and necessary even for law enforcement purposes.<br />3) No legal limitations on what else AT&amp;T can do with this data, who they can share it with, who they can sell it to, etc.<br /><br />Resolve those three and it's fine with me. #1 is a pretty straightforward fix. #2 and #3 in my opinion require passing some real privacy laws, not just limitations on how the government works.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
