not more. They previously were making similar amounts on the NSA data, it was an obvious profit center to open up.<br /><br />It also seems fairly obvious that the same data would be available to the NSA. If nothing else, the NSA and DEA have a data sharing agreement, we've already seen it documented that the NSA will provide data to the DEA, and it follows that the reverse would be true. But more likely the NSA can request the data directly from AT&amp;T using their own administrative subpoenas or national security letters or whatever other non-judicial format they feel like. So even though the NSA only keeps data for 5 years (supposedly), they would have access to 21 more this way.

              

              
              
