        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25212889#p25212889" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Jousle</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">... raises &quot;serious Fourth Amendment concerns.&quot;</div><br /><br />No it doesn't .</div><br /><br />How does the fact that the .gov can get access to my location, via GPS, for any time since I owned a smart phone (~5 years) without a court approved subpoena not infringe on my 4th Amendment?<br /><br />Also, this is a classic example of the .gov using a tool that was approved for one reason (drug enforcement) but is use for completely different reasons as well (bomb threats).

              

              
              
            </div>
