          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25212843#p25212843" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jdale</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25212623#p25212623" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">skicow</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25212559#p25212559" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jdale</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">While technically correct, the Ars article omits an extremely important point from the NYT source:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> It is queried for phone numbers of interest mainly using what are called “administrative subpoenas,” those issued not by a grand jury or a judge but by a federal agency, in this case the D.E.A. </div><br /><br />That's right, this data is received by the DEA with absolutely no court oversight.<br /><br />There is an aspect of this that is important and reasonable. In my opinion, the three problems are:<br />1) No court oversight.<br />2) 26 years is too much data to retain. Far, far beyond what is appropriate and necessary even for law enforcement purposes.<br />3) No legal limitations on what else AT&amp;T can do with this data, who they can share it with, who they can sell it to, etc.<br /><br />Resolve those three and it's fine with me. #1 is a pretty straightforward fix. #2 and #3 in my opinion require passing some real privacy laws, not just limitations on how the government works.</div><br /><br />Agreed -- that is a huge point that is missing from the Ars article.<br /><br />I would also argue why does AT&amp;T need 26 years of call data? The only reason I can think of would be to supply the .gov with it...<br /><br />We really need privacy laws similar to what the EU has...but we'll never get them here I'm afraid because &quot;Corporations are people, my friend&quot;*<br /><br /><br />*no they're not.</div><br /><br />AT&amp;T's motivation is obvious, they are making hundreds of millions of dollars a year on this, if not more. They previously were making similar amounts on the NSA data, it was an obvious profit center to open up.<br /><br />It also seems fairly obvious that the same data would be available to the NSA. If nothing else, the NSA and DEA have a data sharing agreement, we've already seen it documented that the NSA will provide data to the DEA, and it follows that the reverse would be true. But more likely the NSA can request the data directly from AT&amp;T using their own administrative subpoenas or national security letters or whatever other non-judicial format they feel like. So even though the NSA only keeps data for 5 years (supposedly), they would have access to 21 more this way.</div><br /><br />And where do you think the money is coming from? The government is using our money to mak ATT obscenely rich. If there was an argument for not paying federal income ripoff, this is it. We need to stop supporting these abuses with our money.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
